<H1 ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT FACE="Liberation Sans, sans-serif">Aligner</FONT></H1>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT FACE="Liberation Sans, sans-serif"><B>Aligner</B>
performs: </FONT>
</P>
<UL>
	<LI><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY STYLE="margin-bottom: 0cm"><FONT FACE="Liberation Sans, sans-serif">single-word
	term contextual alignment;</FONT></P>
	<LI><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY STYLE="margin-bottom: 0cm"><FONT FACE="Liberation Sans, sans-serif">multi-word
	term compositional alignment;</FONT></P>
	<LI><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY STYLE="margin-bottom: 0cm"><FONT FACE="Liberation Sans, sans-serif">neoclassical
	compound compositional alignment.</FONT></P>
</UL>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY STYLE="margin-bottom: 0cm"><BR>
</P>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT FACE="Liberation Sans, sans-serif">It requires
XMI files previously generated by both the <B>Termer</B> and the
<B>Contextualizer</B> as inputs as well as for the source language as
for the target one.</FONT></P>
<H2 CLASS="western"><FONT FACE="Liberation Sans, sans-serif">Settings</FONT></H2>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT FACE="Liberation Sans, sans-serif"><B>Aligner</B>
requires the following parameters to be set: </FONT>
</P>
<UL>
	<LI><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY STYLE="margin-bottom: 0cm"><FONT FACE="Liberation Sans, sans-serif"><I>Source
	Language</I>: the 2-letter code for the language of text files in
	the source directory; </FONT>
	</P>
	<LI><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY STYLE="margin-bottom: 0cm"><FONT FACE="Liberation Sans, sans-serif"><I>Source
	Terminology File</I>: the XMI file that stands for the source
	terminology; </FONT>
	</P>
	<LI><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY STYLE="margin-bottom: 0cm"><FONT FACE="Liberation Sans, sans-serif"><I>Source
	Term Context Index File</I>: the XMI file of the contextual source
	terminology;</FONT></P>
	<LI><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY STYLE="margin-bottom: 0cm"><FONT FACE="Liberation Sans, sans-serif"><I>Target
	Language</I>: the 2-letter code for the language of text files in
	the target directory; </FONT>
	</P>
	<LI><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY STYLE="margin-bottom: 0cm"><FONT FACE="Liberation Sans, sans-serif"><I>Target
	Terminology File</I>: the file that contains the target term bank; </FONT>
	</P>
	<LI><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY STYLE="margin-bottom: 0cm"><FONT FACE="Liberation Sans, sans-serif"><I>Target
	Term Context Index File</I>: </FONT>
	</P>
	<LI><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY STYLE="margin-bottom: 0cm"><FONT FACE="Liberation Sans, sans-serif"><I>Similarity
	Distance</I>: the class name of the similarity distance ranging
	over; </FONT>
	</P>
	<UL>
		<LI><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY STYLE="margin-bottom: 0cm"><FONT FACE="Liberation Sans, sans-serif">eu.project.ttc.metrics.Jaccard
		for the weighted Jaccard measure;</FONT></P>
		<LI><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY STYLE="margin-bottom: 0cm"><FONT FACE="Liberation Sans, sans-serif">eu.project.ttc.metrics.Cosinus
		for the Cosinus one;</FONT></P>
	</UL>
	<LI><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY STYLE="margin-bottom: 0cm"><FONT FACE="Liberation Sans, sans-serif"><I>Dictionary
	File</I>: the bilingual dictionary; </FONT>
	</P>
	<LI><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT FACE="Liberation Sans, sans-serif"><I>Evaluation
	List File</I>: the terms to translate and their gold standard
	translation.</FONT></P>
</UL>
<H2 CLASS="western">Behaviour</H2>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT FACE="Liberation Sans, sans-serif"><B>Aligner</B>
behaves as follows:</FONT></P>
<UL>
	<LI><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT FACE="Liberation Sans, sans-serif"><B>Aligner</B>
	reads the evaluation list file and builds one CAS per term to
	translate. This CAS document text is given by the term itself. This
	CAS document language is provided by the user through the <I>Source
	Language</I> parameter value.  Aligner provides an annotation of a
	sub-type of <U>TermAnnotation</U> according to the term category
	registered in the evaluation list file. Such term category should
	ranges over</FONT></P>
</UL>
<OL>
	<LI><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT FACE="Liberation Sans, sans-serif">'single-word'
	for providing a <U>SingleWordTermAnnotation</U><SPAN STYLE="text-decoration: none">
	term to translate;</SPAN></FONT></P>
	<LI><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT FACE="Liberation Sans, sans-serif"><SPAN STYLE="text-decoration: none">'multi-word'
	for providing a </SPAN><U>MultiWordTermAnnotation</U><SPAN STYLE="text-decoration: none">
	term;</SPAN></FONT></P>
	<LI><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT FACE="Liberation Sans, sans-serif"><SPAN STYLE="text-decoration: none">'neo-classical-compound'
	for providing a </SPAN><U>NeoClassicalCompoundAnnotation</U><SPAN STYLE="text-decoration: none">
	term;</SPAN></FONT></P>
</OL>
<UL>
	<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT FACE="Liberation Sans, sans-serif">If term
	translations are provided by the evaluation list, <B>Aligner</B>
	annotates the CAS document text by one annotation of the type
	<U>TranslationAnnotation</U><SPAN STYLE="text-decoration: none"> per
	translation where the feature 'term' contains this translation and
	where the feature 'language' is given by the </SPAN><I><SPAN STYLE="text-decoration: none">Target
	Language</SPAN></I><SPAN STYLE="text-decoration: none"> parameter
	value.</SPAN></FONT></P>
	<LI><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT FACE="Liberation Sans, sans-serif"><SPAN STYLE="text-decoration: none"><B>Aligner</B></SPAN><SPAN STYLE="text-decoration: none">
	then selects translation strategy according to the term annotation
	type:</SPAN></FONT></P>
	<LI><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT FACE="Liberation Sans, sans-serif"><SPAN STYLE="text-decoration: none">If
	the term to translate is indexed by a single-word term annotation,
	then the contextual direct method is launch i.e. </SPAN><SPAN STYLE="font-style: normal"><SPAN STYLE="text-decoration: none"><B>Aligner</B></SPAN></SPAN><SPAN STYLE="text-decoration: none">
	draws out the term context vector of the term to translate from the
	source term context index. It filters out every co-located terms of
	this term context that don't belong to the bilingual dictionary. It
	translates every co-located terms of this term context. Then </SPAN><SPAN STYLE="text-decoration: none"><B>Aligner</B></SPAN><SPAN STYLE="text-decoration: none">
	applies the similarity distance for this transferred term context
	over all term contexts of the target term context index. The 100
	best ranked term contexts are filtered in and one annotation of the
	type </SPAN><U>CandidateAnnotation</U><SPAN STYLE="text-decoration: none">
	per filtered target term context is inserting into the current CAS
	with the feature 'translation' that corresponds to the term of this
	filtered target term context, with the features 'score' and 'rank'
	as the results of the similarity distance.</SPAN></FONT></P>
	<LI><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT FACE="Liberation Sans, sans-serif"><SPAN STYLE="text-decoration: none">If
	the term to translate is indexed by a multi-word term annotation,
	then the compositional method is launch e.g. every term components
	are translated, every term component translations are combined
	together and every translated combinations are filtered in if they
	belong to the target terminology. Thus a candidate annotation is
	provided are sorted according to the translation candidate frequency
	in the target terminology.</SPAN></FONT></P>
	<LI><P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><FONT FACE="Liberation Sans, sans-serif"><SPAN STYLE="text-decoration: none">If
	the term to translate is indexed by a neoclassical compound
	annotation, then the compositional strategy is launch after
	pre-processing this neoclassical compound i.e. after checking that
	every term components belong to the bilingual dictionary as well as
	the neoclassical element components as the word ones;</SPAN></FONT></P>
</UL>
